Ear drum ruptured, how long is leaking normal? 35M. Had some pain in my ear yesterday and went to an urgent care and my thoughts proved true as I was diagnosed with an ear infection. Got put on 1000mg of amoxicillin 2x daily for 10 days. Very shortly after the pain began to increase exponentially, and a few hours later, after holding a heating pad to it for a bit, I noticed that water draining feeling in my ear as well as that sound, and saw some clear fluid coming out. Over the next couple of hours that liquid turned to pus and a bit of blood. I read online that when a rupture happens from an ear infection, they'll mostly just prescribe antibiotics which I am already on, and the ear drum should fix itself in 1-2 weeks. My question is how long should it be leaking pus? How much can possibly be in there? Because I'm about 16 or so hours removed from the rupture and it is still leaking pus sort of heavily. Googled articles say 1-3 days but that seems like a lot, considering the amount that's coming out? Can anyone let me know what's up and what's typical?

23M - Colon cancer? Hi there, I've been noticing some strange things with myself lately, and doing a quick search online lead me to suggestions that I might have colon cancer. If this is the case, I can't afford treatment, let alone a doctors visit. Here's  what's been going on though, and apologies for TMI. 

3 or maybe 4 months ago, I noticed that I was pooping less frequently. My diets not the best (cheap junk food and bad balance in general), so I'm no stranger to constipation. So it wasn't anything new. When I was pooping though, and still to this day, the smell is this sickening weird death smell that I haven't had before until now, and the same thing for passing gas. No blood though, or any serious stomach pains which I read is a possible symptom of colon cancer. 

This smell though goes beyond that, and I am constantly smelling it while just passively breathing in. I thought maybe I have some kind of infection somewhere? Besides this though, I've been feeling more tired than normal. I'm an avid coffee drinker so I tried more coffee and that didn't help. No coffee at all, and I felt exactly the same somehow. I'll take a nap and wake up tired. Thought it could be vitamin deficiency but I'm always outside and taking b12s and all that. 

Idk. It would be simple for me to just get looked at because something's clearly up, but I dont't have the finances for anything like chemotherapy or a colonoscopy. If anyone has some words I would definitely appreciate it.

First T/C seizure, then first migraine less than 3 weeks later? So, on September 17 I (21F) had an unprovoked, tonic clonic seizure. The morning of, I woke up at 7am to a bad headache above my right eye that was also on the back of my head on the left side. I had some snacks thinking it might be hunger, no improvement. I later took 600mg ibuprofen, also no improvement. I was putting in an earring (which I've never had a problem with shots, piercings, excision biopsies, etc and i was not nervous or had locked knees or w/e) and after putting it in I immediately got dizzy with tunnel vision. Luckily, my boyfriend was there and held onto me, as I have fainted before and could tell it was coming. I went unconscious seconds after he grabbed me. This is where I know it wasn't fainting: He said my body stiffened and I was still standing while unconscious, I let out a groan, and then mainly my upper body began convulsing. He laid me down in the hallway and the convulsions calmed down. He said at that point my face was turning blue and he thought I needed CPR, so he began compressions. By the third one, I was waking up as if from a deep sleep, and tried to shove him off as if I wanted 5 more minutes. The first thing I could think was how sore I was, as if I went to the gym the day before. I hadn't opened my eyes yet or tried to speak, my hearing seemed muffled. Then I opened my eyes and was able to begin talking within a couple seconds. I had immediate, intense anxiety and was extremely exhausted, also crying for no reason? maybe fear? My headache was also much worse. This has never happened to me and as much as I wanted it to just be fainting, I know its not. I've fainted a handful of times in my life and it's never had any other events/symptoms like this did. I didn't know i was supposed to go to the ER, because I didn't realize it was a seizure. Hey, I'm reaching out for some help, and I'm really hoping you can provide some insight. So, on September 17, I (21F) had my first-ever tonic-clonic seizure. It was a real wake-up call, let me tell you! I woke up at 7am to a bad headache above my right eye that was also on the back of my head on the left side. I thought maybe it was just hunger, but nope, it didn't go away after some snacks. I took 600mg ibuprofen, but that didn't help either. Then, I was putting in an earring (which I've never had a problem with before), and suddenly I got dizzy with tunnel vision. Luckily, my boyfriend was there and held onto me, as I have fainted before and could tell it was coming. I went unconscious seconds after he grabbed me. This is where I know it wasn't just fainting: He said my body stiffened and I was still standing while unconscious, I let out a groan, and then mainly my upper body began convulsing. He laid me down in the hallway and the convulsions calmed down. He said at that point my face was turning blue and he thought I needed CPR, so he began compressions. By the third one, I was waking up as if from a deep sleep, and tried to shove him off as if I wanted 5 more minutes. The first thing I could think was how sore I was, as if I went to the gym the day before. I hadn't opened my eyes yet or tried to speak, my hearing seemed muffled. Then I opened my eyes and was able to begin talking within a couple seconds. I had immediate, intense anxiety and was extremely exhausted, also crying for no reason? maybe fear? My headache was also much worse. This has never happened to me and as much as I wanted it to just be fainting, I know its not. I've fainted a handful of times in my life and it's never had any other events/symptoms like this did. I didn't know I was supposed to go to the ER, because I didn't realize it was a seizure. But I told a telehealth Dr what happened and they said it was a tonic-clonic seizure. I went to a NP at my physician office and she just won't believe me and said I just fainted. So I feel really discouraged.

The rash she described had an acute abrupt onset and would dissipate in just 5-10 minutes.

Rheumatology was consulted, and lab studies were sent to rule out an infectious etiology for the rash. Strep culture was negative, but the DNase B antibody was elevated, and the ASO titer was also high. While she didn't meet clinical criteria for rheumatic fever, the diagnosis most likely entertained was systemic JIA. Further lab work included an ANA which was negative, rheumatoid factor which was negative, a CRP on admission was 8.6 mg/dL with an ESR about 80. CK and aldolase were within normal limits, but ferritin was elevated at 663. LDH was within normal limits, and a CBC was reassuring with normal white counts, hemoglobin, and platelets.

Clinically, she was noted to have a salmon-colored transient rash that would come and go throughout her hospitalization lasting a matter of minutes. No definite arthritis on examination. Oncology was consulted given the history of arthritis and fevers, but they felt that further oncologic evaluation was not indicated, and a bone marrow was not indicated at that time. Cardiology was also consulted because of the 2/6 ejection murmur on the exam, but they felt the murmur was a flow murmur and decided an echo was not indicated to rule out valvular disease in the setting of the rash and arthritis in an attempt to workup acute rheumatic fever.

Please, doctors, help my little sister! She's counting on you!

A patient is experiencing confusion and has no memory of her name, address, or any personal information. She does not recognize her husband nor recall important events of her life. This state of confusion was noticed three days ago. The patient reports that she has not had any recent head injuries or accidents. She has a history of two major depressive episodes within the past four years, which were treated with medication, specifically citalopram, although it is not specified if she is currently taking this medication. There is no information available regarding her family's medical history. Physical and neurological examinations have shown no abnormalities.

A patient has noted a rash on their chest and back which began four days ago starting with a large spot on the right flank before spreading out with smaller, similar spots. The rash is neither painful nor itchy. The patient has not presented with any additional symptoms such as fever, joint pain, or general discomfort associated with the rash. They have not reported recent illnesses like cold or flu prior to the rash's appearance, nor are there any known allergies, use of new body products, or detergents. Furthermore, there is no family history of eczema or similar skin conditions.

A patient has been experiencing early morning headaches for the past 6 months, accompanied by severe nausea and occasional episodes of vomiting. Additionally, the patient recently reported difficulty walking and intermittent double vision. The patient has not noticed any changes in behavior or memory issues and has not experienced any seizures. The patient's health history has been generally good, except for an episode of sinusitis 8 months ago, which resolved without treatment. The patient is not currently taking any medications. The symptoms reportedly do not worsen with changes in position. There is no available information regarding a family history of neurological conditions or similar symptoms.

The patient presents with red scaly bumps on the limbs and face, which fade over weeks and leave smooth white spots. The rash is not affected by sun exposure, and it is neither itchy nor painful. The red bumps reappear every few months and resolve on their own after several weeks. The patient has no personal or family history of autoimmune diseases and has not been using any new medications, skin products, or been exposed to chemicals.

The patient reports feeling well today without any new symptoms to mention. They deny recent experiences of chest pain, shortness of breath, or palpitations. The patient does have a history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and a heart attack which occurred three years ago. There have been no recent changes in the patient's medications. This individual is a 52-year-old man. His father passed away from prostate cancer at the age of 70, but there is no known cardiovascular disease in his family history.

A patient reports experiencing increased urination, dry mouth, and excessive thirst despite consuming several gallons of water daily for the past 2 months. The patient also has a family history of diabetes. There are no mentions of any recent changes in the patient's weight. Additionally, the patient is currently taking citalopram for obsessive-compulsive disorder.

A patient described experiencing recurring skin outbreaks that manifest as red bumps and larger painful lumps. These symptoms appear on her face, neck, chest, and back, typically occurring a week before her menstrual cycle and resolving a week after the cycle. These outbreaks occur once a month, in connection with her menstrual cycle. The patient confirmed that she has not introduced any new skincare products or medications recently. She reported that the outbreaks often leave scarring and dark marks after healing. There's no family history of similar skin issues reported.

A patient reports having multiple thin brown bumps on the face, neck, upper chest, and back, as well as some flat, slightly depressed spots on their palms. The patient's mother first noticed these lesions when the patient was younger. The patient denies having a history of frequent sun exposure or sunburns. The patient affirmatively mentions that their mother developed similar skin lesions at a younger age. The patient's mother also has a history of ovarian fibromas.

A patient reports having sparse hair on their scalp and eyebrows and eczematous patches on their lower legs, symptoms which have been persistent for a long period. The patient does not have a history of any other chronic illnesses or conditions. The patient's son also presents similar symptoms; he has minimal hair, lacks teeth, and has a noticeably large forehead and ears.

A patient presents with sores and bleeding crusts on the lips, along with similar sores in the mouth, genital area, and eyes. Additionally, the patient reports having had a high fever and cough the previous week. The sores began to appear 2 days ago. The patient has not taken any new medications recently, does not have any known allergies, and there is no recent history of similar symptoms among family members or close contacts.

The patient reports feeling very tired and weak, particularly noticeable when engaging in cross-country skiing, with symptoms having started about four weeks ago. The patient denies experiencing shortness of breath, chest pain, or heart palpitations. There is no history of muscle pain or changes in urine color. The patient was diagnosed with pneumonia four weeks ago and received treatment, although the specific antibiotics used are unclear. The patient does not report numbness or loss of sensation in their extremities, nor any recent weight loss or changes in appetite. There is no known family history of heart disease, autoimmune diseases, or other chronic conditions, and the patient has never smoked.

A patient has been suffering from progressively worsening upper abdominal pain for the past six months. The pain is described as dull and exacerbates after eating. Accompanying symptoms include occasional bloating and diarrhea. The patient also reports a significant weight loss during this period. However, there have been no noticeable changes in the color or consistency of the stool nor any presence of blood. The patient has a history of smoking a pack of cigarettes daily for 20 years and consuming 1-2 beers daily. Additionally, the patient has hypertension and hypercholesterolemia and underwent a coronary artery bypass graft operation for coronary artery disease eight years ago. Current medications include lisinopril, metoprolol, atorvastatin, and aspirin. The patient has not provided any information about a family history of gastrointestinal diseases and has not experienced nausea or vomiting but mentions eating very small portions recently.

A patient reports a horn-like growth on their head that has been increasing in size over time and causes pain when accidentally hit. The patient first noticed the small, hard lesion a few months ago. The patient denies any bleeding or discharge from the growth. Unfortunately, the patient does not have additional information to provide. The growth is located on the top part of the head, just to the side of the center.

A patient reports a large area of damaged skin on the scalp, which is hairless and not smooth, and the presence of visible veins on the legs. These symptoms have been present since birth. The patient confirms no other health-related issues originating from birth and there is no known family history of similar symptoms or genetic conditions. The affected area on the scalp shows extensive damage.

A 28-year-old woman presents with a pink bump on her right neck that has increased in size over the past week. The bump easily bleeds when touched or rubbed. She has confirmed that there are no other similar bumps on her body and no history of skin cancer. Furthermore, she hasn't had any chemical exposures, sunburns, or injuries in that area. The bump has remained consistently pink since she first noticed it and does not cause pain or itching.

A patient presents with a dark discoloration on the back of their thighs, which has been present for about a month. The discoloration has remained stable in size and has not significantly grown or changed in texture. The patient reports no pain or itching in the area. Furthermore, the patient has no known allergies, chronic illnesses, or medications. There is no history of similar skin issues or known genetic skin conditions in the patient's family. The patient has not applied any new topical products or made significant changes to their lifestyle or environment.

A patient presents with enlarging blood vessels on their tongue, and small red spots and bumps on the tongue, inside the mouth, nose, lower lip, and fingertips. The patient also reports frequent nosebleeds since childhood and iron-deficiency anemia that has not improved with iron supplements. Their father displayed similar symptoms and passed away at the age of 50.

A patient reports experiencing slurred speech and drooping on the left side of the face. The patient also noticed numbness on the same side. These symptoms have begun about 30 minutes ago. They report no weakness in their limbs or changes in their vision, nor have they had such episodes in the past. The patient has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and hypercholesterolemia, but no other neurological conditions.

The patient has been experiencing tingling pain in the sole of their right foot when lifting it above their chest during exercises. They also suffer from calf cramps in their right leg when using the incline feature on a treadmill. The pain subsides after a few minutes of rest. These symptoms have been occurring for approximately six weeks. Additionally, the patient has been managing type 2 diabetes mellitus for eight years and is taking metformin for this condition. They also have a history of smoking two packs of cigarettes daily for 34 years.

A patient reports that he has been dealing with worsening abdominal pain over the last several months, coupled with feelings of sadness and lack of motivation at work. The patient is a 27-year-old man. His family history includes his father and uncle, both of whom had thyroid cancer and underwent thyroid removal before the age of 30. The patient denies having any symptoms related to digestion, skin, or hair changes, and is not currently taking any medications or supplements.

A patient reports experiencing fever and chest pain during deep breaths, alongside a weight loss of approximately 9 pounds over the last month. The patient denies any recent history of respiratory issues or infections. There are no observed swellings in any areas. The patient is not aware of any family history of cancer or genetic diseases. Additionally, the patient reports no recurrent infections or night sweats recently and confirms no recent travels or exposures to unusual environments or substances. The patient is not currently on any medications and does not suffer from any other underlying health conditions. Despite recent weight loss, the patient hasn't noticed any new lumps or masses on their body.

A patient has been experiencing a rash all over the body which burns and has persisted intermittently for the past year. The appearance and coverage of the rash have remained consistent, showing no changes or spread to new areas. The patient reports that there is no worsening of the rash after exposure to potential triggers such as foods, medications, or environmental factors. The patient does not have a history of any allergies, or atopic conditions like asthma or eczema. Attempts at using antihistamines to alleviate the rash were unsuccessful. Additionally, the patient experiences no joint pain, abdominal pain, or fever accompanying the rash. There is no noted history of similar skin issues or chronic skin conditions in the patient's family.

A patient developed erosions and blisters on the surfaces of their palms and soles which have been presenting since day 2 of their life. The patient doesn't have any known allergies and reports no exposure to new medications or chemicals. There are no similar symptoms nor any known genetic diseases in the family. The blisters cause no pain or itching and no other areas besides the palms and soles are affected.

A patient is reporting pain in both knees and severe pain over the right groin area. Additionally, the patient describes that the right leg appears slightly shorter, is bent, turned inward, and is pulled toward the middle. These symptoms have been experienced since the patient was involved in a rear-end collision earlier today. The patient confirms having no previous medical conditions or surgeries related to the hips or legs.

The patient presents with feelings of loneliness and emotional instability, experiencing mood swings that range from intense happiness and affection to periods of depression. These symptoms have been persistent for at least the past year. The patient's mood swings appear to be influenced by interactions and relationship difficulties with their boyfriend. There are no reported changes in energy levels, sleep patterns, or appetite accompanying the mood swings. Additionally, the patient is not currently receiving any medications or treatments for the emotional and mood-related symptoms.

A patient reports having itchy spots on the palms, soles, and ankles. These symptoms have been intermittently appearing for the past 6 months. The patient reveals that no clear triggers for the spots have been identified, and the spots form blisters. The patient does not report any issues with digestion or changes in stool, and denies any known allergies or previous history of skin diseases. There is no information provided about family history or similar symptoms in family members.

A patient has been experiencing tender bumps on their shins for the past three months. They report that the bumps have not changed in color or size. The patient does not experience any other symptoms such as joint pain, abdominal pain, or fever. They have no known chronic illnesses like diabetes or inflammatory bowel disease, and there is no family history of skin conditions or autoimmune diseases. Additionally, the patient is not currently taking any medications and has not started any new medications in the past year.

The patient has been experiencing fever, weakness, diffuse abdominal pain, and multiple lumps on the body over the past week. The patient reports that the lumps seem to be deeper, resembling those in the glands. There have been no changes noted in the color or consistency of the patient's stools. The patient has not experienced any unintentional weight loss, night sweats, chills, skin lesions, or unusual bruising, as these symptoms are not mentioned in the case vignette. Recently, the patient returned to the USA after a 3-month agricultural internship in South America.

A patient reports a loss of appetite and a weight loss of 15 pounds over the past three months. The patient denies experiencing any changes in bowel habits or gastrointestinal symptoms. Furthermore, the patient does not have fever, night sweats, or chronic fatigue. There are no known medical conditions in their history, and the patient is not on any medications. There is no similar health history among family members, including chronic diseases like cancer or autoimmune disorders. However, the patient expresses a conscious desire to lose more weight and is careful about not becoming overweight.

A patient, a 32-year-old man, has been experiencing increasing shortness of breath when exerting himself over the past three months. He reports that the shortness of breath occurs only on exertion and improves with rest. The patient mentions that there is no swelling in his legs or feet and confirms that he does not suffer from any preexisting health conditions or diagnosed heart or lung diseases. Additionally, there is no information provided about any smoking habits or exposure to harmful substances, nor is there any information about his family’s medical history in his case details.

A 9-year-old girl has been experiencing early morning headaches accompanied by nausea for several months, occasionally leading to vomiting which provides some relief. Furthermore, she has been feeling very fatigued and has had trouble maintaining balance, causing her to discontinue her ballet classes. There are no reported changes in her vision, mood, or memory. She reports no recent falls or head injuries. There is no known family history of neurological disorders or genetic diseases. She has consulted a doctor, and an MRI of the brain has been performed, although specific details and results of the scan are not available. She has not experienced any issues related to her growth or development.

A patient reports difficulties with sleeping and poor concentration at work, which have persisted for about three weeks. The patient also describes feeling depressed and experiencing low mood. The patient disclosed that these symptoms began following a sexual assault that occurred three weeks ago, which has been a source of considerable stress. The patient has not received any specific treatment or psychological support since the incident.

A patient has been experiencing increasing shortness of breath over the past three months and finds it challenging to climb three flights of stairs to their apartment. They report having a fever, but no chest pain or cough. There has been no noticeable swelling in the legs or recent weight gain. The patient was diagnosed with HIV six years ago. Currently, they are on triple antiretroviral therapy for their HIV but confess to frequently missing doses. The patient has not reported any recent infections such as pneumonia or tuberculosis.

A patient presents with brown spots on their upper and lower lips as well as on their hands, which have been present for several years. The spots are painless and do not cause itchiness. There haven't been any changes in the size, shape, or color of the spots over time. The patient does not have similar spots on their face or neck, nor do they have a history of extensive sun exposure or use of tanning beds. Additionally, the patient does not experience any other symptoms such as dry skin, increased thirst, or frequent urination. There is no family history of similar brown spots. The patient has no other medical conditions and is not taking any medications.

A patient has been experiencing acute pain and warmth in a spot on their neck for the past three days. The skin around the spot has not changed color, but it is tender and there is a presence of a soft nodule. The nodule’s mobility or any change in size has not been specified. The patient has not had recent infections or injuries in that area. Additionally, there is no mention of a history of similar issues or other medical conditions. Also, there's no family history of skin or gland-related disorders mentioned.

A patient has been dealing with pain in their right leg for the past month. The patient, who is 14 years old, reports no changes in color or temperature in the affected leg. The patient experiences persistent pain that does not improve at night, leading their mother to administer sleep aid medications. There have been no recent injuries or infections, and there is no known family history of bone diseases or similar symptoms. Additionally, the patient does not observe any swelling, lumps, or reduced mobility in the leg, nor are there any accompanying symptoms such as fever, weight loss, or night sweats. A recent X-ray of the right lower extremity revealed several lytic lesions in the middle part of the thigh bone and several layers of new bone around the cortex.

A patient presents with reddish-brown patches in their underarms that have persisted for six months. The patches do not cause any itchiness or discomfort. There have been no recent changes in the patient's health, nor have any new medications been started before the appearance of these patches. The patient does not have a history of diabetes, obesity, or insulin resistance. There has been no mention of any family history of similar skin conditions or other dermatological issues. Additionally, the patient has not tried any treatments or remedies for the patches so far.

A patient, 36 years old, reports experiencing pelvic discomfort and heavy menstrual bleeding for about a year. She has not been diagnosed with fibroids or other reproductive health issues, nor has she noticed an increase in abdominal size or feelings of fullness when not eating much. Her menstrual cycles occur at regular 30-day intervals. There is no known family history of gynecological conditions like fibroids, endometriosis, or cancers. She has not experienced any changes in bowel habits or urinary frequency and has not undergone any imaging studies such as an ultrasound of the pelvis. The patient agrees to schedule an ultrasound to assess the pelvic region.

A patient has been experiencing a persistent cough accompanied by white phlegm and frequent episodes throughout the day for about 4 months. Additionally, the patient encounters shortness of breath upon exertion. The individual has a 30-year history of smoking a pack of cigarettes daily and has been working in construction for the past 10 years. The patient reports no recent weight loss, fever, or chills. The patient also has hypertension and is being treated with amlodipine.

A patient reports having a dry cough and worsening shortness of breath over the past two months, with no specific triggers identified. The symptoms have progressively worsened over time. The patient has a history of smoking one pack of cigarettes daily for 45 years. The patient has not experienced fever, chills, or night sweats, and was previously healthy. The patient does not report taking any medications or having other medical conditions.

A patient reports having experienced fatigue, weight loss, and abdominal pain over the past six months. The patient denies any changes in bowel habits or presence of blood in the stool. The patient has no prior history of medical conditions and has not observed any recent night sweats or fevers. The patient is unaware of any family history regarding cancer or gastrointestinal diseases and hasn’t noted any enlargement or discomfort in the lymph nodes. The patient confirms a loss of appetite but denies experiencing nausea or vomiting. No imaging tests or blood work related to these symptoms have been conducted recently.

A 19-year-old man presents with mild chest pain and shortness of breath, which has been ongoing for a little over half an hour. He reports no past medical history of heart disease or other chronic conditions and is not currently on any medications. The patient also has no family history of heart disease or other cardiovascular disorders. He was recently involved in a high-speed motor vehicle collision.

A patient has been experiencing progressive fatigue and lower back pain for the past 4 months, which has significantly worsened since a minor fall yesterday. The patient reports no changes in appetite or weight recently and has no information about their family history of cancer to share. Additionally, the patient does not report fever, night sweats, or unintentional weight loss. The patient has no information about previous medical conditions or surgeries, and also does not have information on any current or recent medications. They have not been diagnosed or treated for blood-related disorders or cancers previously. The patient denies any numbness, tingling, or weakness in the legs but mentions experiencing a feeling of incomplete emptying of the bladder after voiding for the past year; however, they have no difficulties with bowel movements.

A patient has reported intermittent chest pain described as burning, intentional weight loss, and small nonhealing ulcers on the fingertips, persisting for approximately two months. The patient denies experiencing joint pain, dry eyes, or dry mouth. Additionally, there are no symptoms of shortness of breath or a persistent cough. However, the patient has noted fine crackling sounds upon inhalation. The patient does not have a personal or familial history of autoimmune diseases. There has been no exposure to new medications or environmental factors such as chemicals or radiation recently.

A patient reports experiencing upper abdominal pain that worsens after eating, along with nausea, heartburn, and episodes of diarrhea for the past 12 months. According to the patient, ingesting food generally exacerbates the pain. The patient denies any weight loss. Current medications include pantoprazole and over-the-counter antacids, with no reported regular use of NSAIDs. The patient does not report any familial history of gastrointestinal problems, nor have they noticed any blood in their stool or vomit.

A patient presents with oval-shaped lesions on the arms, which first appeared a few months ago. Initially, these lesions were red and then hardened before transitioning into a dark, smooth, and shiny appearance. The lesions have been confined to the arms and have not spread to other parts of the body. The patient reports a family history of rheumatoid arthritis but no personal history of similar skin issues or other chronic diseases. Additionally, the lesions are neither itchy nor painful. The patient confirms not having started any new medications or treatments prior to the appearance of these lesions.

The patient reports a white discoloration on her left breast that occasionally itches, first noticed 6 months ago. There has been no noticeable spreading or changes in the discoloration since its initial observation. She does not exhibit similar patches on other parts of her body, nor does she have a personal or family history of skin conditions or diseases. There has been no use of new skin products or exposure to different environmental factors prior to noticing the discoloration.

A 14-year-old female patient presents for evaluation due to being shorter than expected for her age. Her breast and pubic hair development are recorded to be at Tanner stage 2, indicative of a developmental delay. There is no family history of growth or developmental delays mentioned. No prior evaluations or treatments for her condition have been documented. Additionally, there are no reported issues with her sense of smell.

A five-week-old infant is experiencing breathing difficulties, including noticeable indentations below the ribs while breathing. The infant has no difficulties with feeding or unusual crying during feeding. No episodes of bluish discoloration around the lips or fingertips have been reported. It is not specified whether the breathing difficulty changes with different positions. There is no known family history of respiratory or cardiac diseases. The infant has a history of hospitalization, requiring intubation and mechanical ventilation for a month, and has been on noninvasive pressure ventilation for the past five days.

A patient has been noticing multiple spots on their face since adolescence, and these spots have been increasing in number over time. The spots are light in color or match the patient's skin tone and are shaped like small domes. There's no itching or pain associated with the spots, and they do not bleed, even after mild trauma or friction. Some family members of the patient have experienced similar skin issues.

A 55-year-old patient reports the development of fine wrinkles over the past year on various areas of their body, including the neck, chest, axilla (armpits), trunk, back, and upper arms. The patient has not noticed any changes in texture or thickness such as hardening or thinning of the skin. Additionally, there have been no symptoms of dryness, itching, or changes in skin color in the affected areas. The patient has no history of skin disorders or other significant health problems, and they are not currently taking any medications. Furthermore, there is no known family history of similar skin issues or genetic disorders.

A patient reports having a mildly itchy rash on the thigh and buttock, which began as a red dot and has rapidly expanded, now featuring some white flakes in the center. This rash has been present for approximately five days. The patient denies recent contact with new plants, animals, substances, and has not traveled recently. Additionally, the patient reports no other symptoms such as fever, joint pain, or swollen lymph nodes. There is no personal or family history of skin conditions or autoimmune diseases. The patient is not currently on any medications and has not started any new medications recently.

A patient reports experiencing shortness of breath, right-sided chest pain, right upper quadrant abdominal pain, and right shoulder pain for approximately 15 minutes. The patient claims to be otherwise healthy, not taking any medications, but recently had a fall down a flight of stairs. Subsequent to the fall, the patient has multiple bruises over the right chest area and experiences tenderness when it is touched.

A 73-year-old patient has been experiencing increasing forgetfulness over the past two years, often forgetting daily activities like television content or reading material from the previous day. Recently, the patient also got lost during a usual morning walk and has subsequently stopped going on these walks. The patient reports becoming easily agitated when asked questions directly, encountering difficulty finding the right words during conversations, and making errors with tasks that involve numeric sequences. However, the patient has not noticed any change in coordination or movement. There is no available information regarding the family history of neurological disorders. The patient is currently on medication including aspirin, enalapril, carvedilol, and atorvastatin, prescribed for conditions like hypertension, coronary artery disease, and hypercholesterolemia.

A patient reports having a persistent rash on their scalp and forehead, described as red and scaly, which worsens in cold weather. This condition has been ongoing for several weeks. The patient denies experiencing joint pain, fatigue, or other related symptoms. No treatments or medications have been attempted to resolve the rash. It is noted that the patient's father has a history of psoriasis.

The patient has been suffering from headaches that are worse in the mornings and has noticed a deterioration in their peripheral vision. They have been experiencing these symptoms for approximately 8 months. There are no accompanying symptoms of nausea, vomiting, or dizziness reported. The patient's previous health record shows no illnesses and they are not currently on any medications. There are also no noted changes in weight, appetite, energy levels, body hair, or skin condition. Moreover, there is no known family history of endocrine or neurological disorders mentioned.

A patient reports observing a purple area on the right arm that has been expanding over the past month. The patient experiences no pain or itching in the specified area. The patient has a medical history which includes high cholesterol, for which they are taking simvastatin, as well as previously treated skin cancer and breast cancer. The purple area exhibits some ulceration; however, there are no specified changes in the texture or reports of the area being raised. There is no family history of similar skin issues or skin cancer reported in this case.

A 3-day-old newborn is facing several health challenges including generalized convulsions, lethargy, difficulty feeding, and yellowish skin. The infant was delivered vaginally at 36 weeks, which is slightly premature as full term is usually around 40 weeks. A cranial ultrasonography on the infant revealed ventricular dilatation and some abnormal areas within the brain.

A newborn, just born 12 hours ago, is presenting with frequent greenish vomiting and noticeable swelling in the upper belly. The newborn has not passed any stool since birth. There are no reported signs of discoloration or abnormalities near the anus, and no family history of similar symptoms has been provided.

A patient is experiencing a rash on the trunk that has spread to the hands, feet, and ears. Accompanying symptoms include fevers, chills, and diarrhea, which started on day 30 post therapy. The patient recently underwent a hematopoietic stem cell transplant. No specific infections or complications relating to the transplant have been diagnosed. The symptoms, such as the rash and gastrointestinal issues like diarrhea, may suggest the possibility of graft-versus-host disease (GVHD).

A patient reports suffering from headaches, blurred vision, and confusion over the past two weeks. The patient denies any recent head injuries or accidents. The patient has an HIV infection and is currently receiving antiretroviral therapy along with trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole. This is the first occurrence of these symptoms for the patient. There is no family history of similar symptoms or diagnosed neurological conditions.

A 35-year-old construction worker presents with a well-circumscribed, verrucous plaque on his left upper arm. The lesion has been present for a few months, but recently has increased in size and become painful. He reports that a cough preceded his skin lesion, but otherwise has no relevant medical history. A large verrucous and ulcerating lesion with pustules is seen. On palpation, a purulent discharge is expressed.

A 16-year-old male with past medical history of mitral valve prolapse presents for evaluation of loose skin. Patient's parents report a several year history of stretchy skin, poor wound healing with some scars healing with thin overlying skin, and easy bruising. There is a family history of similar symptoms amongst other family members. Physical examination reveals soft, significantly extensible skin diffusely, multiple linear scars with atrophic overlying pink patches, and white-yellow papules along the bilateral inner and outer calcaneus upon standing. The patient is able to touch the tip of his nose with his tongue.

A 45-year-old man presents to the primary care clinic with a red, itchy rash on the eyebrows and around the nose that has been ongoing for eight months. He has tried moisturizers to the areas, but the flakiness returns a few days later. He also reports he has dandruff in his scalp. He denies any new facial products or using any other creams or lotions.   Physical examination reveals greasy yellow scale on poorly demarcated erythematous patches on the eyebrows and bilateral nasal alar creases. Mild white scale is appreciated diffusely across the scalp.

A 70-year-old man presents with 1 year of a non-healing growth on the right cheek. He says he first noticed it when he accidentally bumped into it and it bled easily. He denies any preceding trauma to the lesion.

A 62-year-old man with well-controlled rosacea, a monoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance, and chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL; stable on no current therapy) was seen in the clinic for a full-body skin check. Results of his examination were unremarkable except for the presence of periorbital, yellow-brown plaques with violaceous borders involving the upper and lower eyelids, bilaterally. There was induration, but no warmth or tenderness, of the periorbital plaques. He first noticed these lesions around the time he was diagnosed with CLL; initially they were more discrete yellow papules that developed into plaques over time. They are completely asymptomatic.

A 32-year-old male with past medical history of poorly controlled HIV presents to clinic with dark spots on the skin and in the mouth. He cannot recall when they first started. He denies any drug or alcohol use. He is not currently taking his antiretroviral therapy. Examination reveals multiple ovoid violaceous ruddy, brown ovoid macules on the trunk, legs, oral palate and plantar feet. A punch biopsy is performed and stains for HHV-8 is positive.

A 63-year-old woman comes to the emergency department because of a 1-day history of progressive blurring and darkening of her vision in the right eye. Upon waking up in the morning, she suddenly started seeing multiple dark streaks. She has migraines and type 2 diabetes mellitus diagnosed at her last health maintenance examination 20 years ago. She has smoked one pack of cigarettes daily for 40 years. Her only medication is sumatriptan. Her vitals are within normal limits. Ophthalmologic examination shows visual acuity of 20/40 in the left eye and 20/100 in the right eye. The fundus is obscured and difficult to visualize on fundoscopic examination of the right eye. The red reflex is diminished on the right.

A 54-year-old woman comes to the physician because of a painful skin lesion on her right leg for 1 month. It initially started out as a small red spot but has rapidly increased in size during this period. She remembers an ant bite on her leg prior to the lesion occurring. She was treated for anterior uveitis 8 months ago with corticosteroids. She has Crohn's disease, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and hypertension. Current medications include insulin, mesalamine, enalapril, and aspirin. She returned from Wisconsin after visiting her son 2 months ago. Her temperature is 37.6°C (98°F), pulse is 98/min, and blood pressure is 126/88 mm Hg. Examination shows pitting pedal edema of the lower extremities. There is a 4-cm tender ulcerative lesion on the anterior right leg with a central necrotic base and purplish irregular borders. There are dilated tortuous veins in both lower legs. Femoral and pedal pulses are palpated bilaterally.

A 45-year-old woman comes to the physician because of shortness of breath while lying on her back over the past month. During this period, she has also had several episodes of bloody coughing. The patient reports that she had a heart problem when she was a child that was treated with antibiotics. She emigrated to the US from Russia 5 years ago. There is no family history of serious illness. Pulmonary examination shows crackles at both lung bases. Cardiac examination is shown. An ECG shows tachycardia and no P waves.

A 21-year-old woman comes to the physician because of multiple painful, purulent ulcers she noticed on her vulva 2 days ago. The patient has not had fever or burning with urination. She has no history of similar lesions. She had a chlamydial infection at 17 years of age that was treated with antibiotics. Her immunizations are up-to-date. She is sexually active with her boyfriend of 2 months and uses an oral contraceptive; they use condoms inconsistently. Her temperature is 37.2°C (99.0°F), pulse is 94/min, and blood pressure is 120/76 mm Hg. Examination shows tender inguinal lymphadenopathy. There are 4 tender, purulent 1.5-cm ulcers with a necrotic base along the labia majora.

A 30-year-old woman comes to the primary care physician because she has felt nauseous and fatigued for 3 weeks. Menses occur at irregular 24- to 33-day intervals and last for 4–6 days. Her last menstrual period was 7 weeks ago. Her temperature is 37°C (98.6°F), pulse is 95/min, and blood pressure is 100/70 mm Hg. Pelvic examination shows an enlarged uterus. Her serum β-hCG concentration is 96,000 mIU/mL (N < 5). An abdominal ultrasound is shown.

A healthy 30-year-old man presents with a 3-year history of an asymptomatic, fleshy papule at the base of his great toe. He denies any new lesions during this time, a history of trauma to the area, or a family history of similar skin lesions. He was treated previously by another dermatologist with cryotherapy; however, he returns to the clinic with recurrence of the lesion. Examination reveals a pedunculated, flesh-colored, well-demarcated tumor on the plantar surface of the base of his great toe.

A fullterm newborn African American male is noticed by nursing staff to have multiple dark spots on the head and neck present at birth. The patient was born via spontaneous vaginal delivery and had an unremarkable prenatal course. Examination reveals scattered collarettes of scale on the face and neck and few ovoid hyperpigmented macules scattered on the neck. Remainder of exam was unremarkable.

A 56-year-old woman comes to the physician because of a 2-week history of fatigue and painless bruising over her arms and trunk. She has also had several episodes of nosebleeds that resolved with compression after a few minutes. She recently completed treatment for a urinary tract infection. She has had no changes in her weight. She has type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension. Her last menstrual cycle was 5 years ago. She does not smoke or drink alcohol. Home medications include metformin, amlodipine, and enalapril. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Physical examination shows pale conjunctivae. There are ecchymoses and petechiae over the upper extremities, chest, and back. There is no lymphadenopathy. The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable. Laboratory studies show:
Hemoglobin 8.7 mg/dL
Leukocyte count 1100/mm3
Platelet count 54,000/mm3
Reticulocyte count 0.1%
Mean corpuscular volume 93 μm3
Serum
Total bilirubin 1.1 mg/dL
LDH 80 U/L

Six hours after delivery, a 3050-g (6-lb 12-oz) male newborn is noted to have feeding intolerance and several episodes of bilious vomiting. He was born at term to a healthy 35-year-old woman following a normal vaginal delivery. The pregnancy was uncomplicated, but the patient's mother had missed several of her prenatal checkups. The patient's older brother underwent surgery for pyloric stenosis as an infant. Vital signs are within normal limits. Physical examination shows epicanthus, upward slanting of the eyelids, low-set ears, and a single transverse palmar crease. The lungs are clear to auscultation. A grade 2/6 holosystolic murmur is heard at the left mid to lower sternal border. Abdominal examination shows a distended upper abdomen and a concave-shaped lower abdomen. There is no organomegaly. An x-ray of the abdomen is shown.

A 45-year-old man comes to the physician for a routine health maintenance examination. He feels well. He underwent appendectomy at the age of 25 years. He has a history of hypercholesterolemia that is well controlled with atorvastatin. He is an avid marathon runner and runs 8 miles per day four times a week. His father died of myocardial infarction at the age of 42 years. The patient does not smoke or drink alcohol. His vital signs are within normal limits. Cardiopulmonary examination shows no abnormalities. His abdomen is soft and nontender with a surgical scar in the right lower quadrant. Laboratory studies are within normal limits. An ECG is shown.

A 64-year-old woman comes to the physician because of several episodes of dizziness during the last month. The episodes last between 30–40 seconds and during the episodes she feels as though she is spinning. Episodes usually occur immediately after lying down or suddenly sitting up from a reclined position. They also sometimes happen when she suddenly turns her head to look at something. She has no nausea. Last month, she had an upper respiratory tract infection that resolved spontaneously. She has hypertension treated with hydrochlorothiazide. Otoscopic examination shows no abnormalities. There is no lateralization when a vibrating 512 Hz tuning fork is placed in the middle of the forehead.

A 7-year-old girl is brought to the emergency department because she has had abdominal pain and vomiting for the past day. The pain is intermittent, diffuse in nature, and worse after meals. She does not have loose or bloody stools. She has had a nonpruritic rash on her legs and swelling of her ankles for 6 days. She was treated with oral amoxicillin for a sore throat 2 weeks ago. Her immunizations are up-to-date. Vital signs are within normal limits. Examination of the lower extremities shows non-blanching, raised erythematous papules. The left ankle joint is swollen and warm, and its range of motion is limited by pain. Abdominal examination shows tenderness to palpation in the left lower quadrant without guarding or rebound. Bowel sounds are normal. Test of the stool for occult blood is positive. Laboratory studies show:
Hemoglobin 10.1 g/dL
Leukocyte count
11,800/mm3
Platelet count 431,000/mm3
Erythrocyte sedimentation rate 45 mm/h
Serum
Glucose 72 mg/dL
Creatinine 0.9 mg/dL

A 15-year-old Black man presents with a 1-year history of light spots on his back. The rash has grown slowly, with several new lesions appearing near the first one. It is not itchy or painful. He has not tried any treatments for this condition. He has no relevant medical history and none of his family members have similar skin findings. On examination, there are several well-demarcated depigmented macules and patches on his lateral back.

A 19-year-old female college student comes to the physician for a sudden loss of visual acuity of her right eye. She noticed that she was unable to read the time on the alarm clock when she woke up in the morning. When she closes her right eye, she is able to see sharply. When she closes her left eye, she has blurry double vision. She does not recall trauma to her eye but has been working long nights on her honors thesis. She has a history of occasional shoulder luxation. She is 180 cm (5 ft 11 in) tall, and weighs 62 kg (136 lbs); her BMI is 19.1 kg/m2. Her vital signs are within normal limits. On physical examination, slender and long fingers are noted. She has several flat, demarcated brownish nevi on her left cheek. Ocular examination shows upward temporal subluxation of her right lens.

A 29-year-old woman with a history of acne presents to the clinic with 3 discrete, atrophic, blue-tinged plaques on her face. The plaques were located on her forehead and cheeks bilaterally. The patient states the lesions had been present for several months and had slowly worsened until they stabilized at their current appearance. The patient reported that the lesions occurred after she went to a physician for “acne treatment.” The patient has no other medical conditions or relevant social history.

A 32-year-old man is brought to the emergency department 15 minutes after falling 7 feet onto a flat-top wooden post. On arrival, he is in severe pain and breathing rapidly. His pulse is 135/min, respirations are 30/min, and blood pressure is 80/40 mm Hg. There is an impact wound in the left fourth intercostal space at the midaxillary line. Auscultation shows tracheal deviation to the right and absent breath sounds over the left lung. There is dullness to percussion over the left chest. Neck veins are flat. Cardiac examination shows no abnormalities. Two large-bore intravenous catheters are placed and intravenous fluid resuscitation is begun.

A 40-year-old female presents with a recurrent skin eruption on her nose and cheeks for 2 years. These lesions appears usually in the summer following excessive sun exposure, and disappears without scarring. She has complains about arthritis and chronic fatigue. She denies muscle weakness. Physical exam reveals eroded butterfly-shaped erythematous plaques over the malar area, non-scarring alopecia and oral ulcers.

The patient is a 46-year-old woman who presents at your primary care office for an examination with a single lesion that appears on her left arm. During the examination, it is revealed that the patient has a large sclerotic, indurated, hyperpigmented, anhidrotic, and hairless plaque on the right dorsal forearm. The patient states that these lesions had previously been slightly pink for several months before they had turned brown in color and had become “hard.” The patient has type 2 diabetes, but she has no other medical problems. In addition, she has no relevant social or family history.

A 38-year-old woman comes to the physician for a 3-month history of bloody discharge from the right nipple. Her mother died of breast cancer at the age of 69 years. Mammography 6 months ago did not show any abnormalities. Examination of the breast shows expression of a small amount of serosanguinous fluid from the right nipple; there are no palpable breast masses or axillary lymphadenopathy. Ultrasonography of the right breast shows a single dilated duct.

A 13-year-old boy presents to the dermatology clinic concerned about the development of red, itchy, and sometimes painful bumps on his fingers. He first noted seeing the lesions 2 months prior, in early December. Although the initial lesions have since resolved, new lesions appeared after a skiing trip the previous weekend. The patient is otherwise healthy, with no significant past medical history, and he does not take any medications. Physical examination reveals erythematous, tender papules on the lateral and dorsal aspects of the distal fingers.

A 45-year-old man with a past medical history of hypertension presents with concerns of a rash on his left thigh back that his wife noticed two days ago. The rash has been progressively enlargened. Patient denies any pain or any prior treatments. He thinks the surrounding skin is warm and may be infected, but he denies any drainage.  He reports that they went hiking eight days ago in Rhode Island.   Physical exam demonstrates a non-scaly large targetoid, pink-red patch on the left thigh

A 19-year-old woman is brought to the physician by her parents because of irritable mood that started 5 days ago. Since then, she has been staying up late at night working on a secret project. She is energetic despite sleeping less than 4 hours per day. Her parents report that she seems easily distracted. She is usually very responsible, but this week she spent her paycheck on supplies for her project. She has never had similar symptoms before. In the past, she has had episodes where she felt too fatigued to go to school and slept until 2 pm every day for 2 weeks at a time. During those times, her parents noticed that she cried excessively, was very indecisive, and expressed feelings of worthlessness. Two months ago, she had an asthma exacerbation and was treated with bronchodilators and steroids. She tried cocaine once in high school but has not used it since. Vital signs are within normal limits. On mental status examination, she is irritable but cooperative. Her speech is pressured and her thought process is linear.

A 21-year-old male presents for evaluation of a painful rash on his right index finger. He reports a tingling sensation prior to the eruption of red small spots that became more yellow and pus filled. He denies any trauma or topical products applied to the area. He has a history of cold sores on the lips. Physical examination reveals multiple clustered painful, white-yellow vesicles on the right index finger on erythematous pink base.

A 15-year-old white adolescent presents to the dermatology clinic with an asymptomatic rash on his upper back that has persisted for 4 months. Physical examination reveals hyperpigmented scaly papules coalescing into confluent plaques with peripheral reticulated papillomatosis. The boy is overweight but has no history of any other medical conditions.

A 28-year-old woman comes to the physician because of a 1-year history of intermittent buzzing in both her ears. She says she sometimes has episodes of mild dizziness which resolve spontaneously. She has a 15-year history of type 1 diabetes mellitus and episodes of low back pain. She does not smoke or drink alcohol. Current medications include insulin and aspirin. She works as a trombonist for a symphony orchestra. Her vital signs are within normal limits. On otoscopic examination, the tympanic membrane appears normal. Bone conduction is greater than air conduction in both ears. Weber test shows no lateralization.

A 34-year-old male presents with history of itching all over the body ongoing for the past year. He does not take any medications other than multivitamins. He denies any history of skin conditions. He has tried fexofenadine in the past which helped, but over the counter hydrocortisone only provides minimal relief. Pruritus is worse around areas of tight clothing contacting his skin that occurs within a few minutes. Skin examination reveals linear urticaria on the upper back that develop after two minutes in areas of gentle scratching with a cotton tip applicator.

A 76-year-old woman is brought to the physician because of lesions on her left arm. She first noticed them 3 months ago and they have grown larger since that time. She has not had any pain or pruritus in the area. She has a history of invasive ductal carcinoma of the left breast, which was treated with mastectomy and radiation therapy 27 years ago. Since that time, she has had lymphedema of the left arm. Physical examination shows extensive edema of the left arm. There are four coalescing, firm, purple-blue nodules on the left lateral axillary region and swelling of the surrounding skin.

A 75-year-old male presents with a few day history of blisters developing on his arms and legs. He denies any exposures to poison ivy, any recent travel, and any recent medication changes. Physical examination demonstrates thin urticarial pink plaques on the abdomen and multiple tense bullae without significant underlying erythema scattered on the arms and legs.

A 13-month-old toddler with spreading eczema on his trunk and arms is brought in by his mother. She is applying moisturizer and a cortisone cream. However, 2 days earlier, a wound appeared on his left hand that appears to be infected. Since then, more areas of raw, oozing skin have developed. Examination reveals lichenified scaling plaques scattered on the trunk and posterior knees and arms, and his left arm has monomorphic crusted vesicles and ulcerations on an erythematous base.

A 34-year-old man with AIDS comes to the physician because of a 2-day history of decreasing vision and seeing black spots in his right eye. He has no pain and the left eye is asymptomatic. He was treated for fungal esophagitis 6 months ago with fluconazole. He was diagnosed with Kaposi's sarcoma 2 years ago. Current medications include efavirenz, tenofovir, emtricitabine, azithromycin, trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, multivitamins, and a nutritional supplement. He is 170 cm (5 ft 7 in) tall and weighs 45 kg (99 lbs);BMI is 15.6 kg/m2. His temperature is 37°C (98.6°F), pulse is 89/min, and blood pressure is 110/70 mm Hg. Examination shows cervical lymphadenopathy. There are multiple violaceous plaques seen over his trunk and extremities. Fundoscopic examination shows granular yellow-white opacities around the retinal vessels and multiple areas of dot-blot hemorrhages. His CD4+ T-lymphocyte count is 36/mm3.

A 60-year-old man comes to the physician because of a 3-month history of a slowly enlarging painless ulcer on his lower lip. One year ago he had a painful rash near his upper lip that resolved completely with acyclovir therapy. He has a 10-year history of type 2 diabetes mellitus treated with metformin. He has worked in construction for the past 33 years. He has smoked one pack of cigarettes daily for 35 years. Examination shows a 0.5 x 0.5 cm nontender ulcer with everted edges on the midline of his lower lip. The erythematous ulcer bleeds upon palpation. He has numerous moles of varying sizes all over his body. There are no palpable cervical lymph nodes.

A 14-year-old boy is brought to the physician for the evaluation of back pain for the past six months. The pain is worse with exercise and when reclining. He attends high school and is on the swim team. He also states that he lifts weights on a regular basis. He has not had any trauma to the back or any previous problems with his joints. He has no history of serious illness. His father has a disc herniation. Palpation of the spinous processes at the lumbosacral area shows that two adjacent vertebrae are displaced and are at different levels. Muscle strength is normal. Sensation to pinprick and light touch is intact throughout. When the patient is asked to walk, a waddling gait is noted. Passive raising of either the right or left leg causes pain radiating down the ipsilateral leg.

A 42-year-old man presents with a four-day history of experiencing headache, malaise, and stabbing right-sided headache. Two days after his initial symptoms appeared, he developed a rash over the area of pain. He reports that he went hiking through the Texas hill country prior to becoming ill. The patient is otherwise in good health and has an unremarkable medical history. Physical examination reveals unilateral erythematous, thin, raised plaques over the right forehead. In addition, he has no relevant social or family history.

A 28-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department after being found in a confused state on an interstate rest area in Florida. She is unable to recall her name, address, or any other information regarding her person. She denies being the woman on a Connecticut driver's license found in her wallet. A telephone call with the police department of her hometown reveals that she had been reported missing three days ago by her husband. When the husband arrives, he reports that his wife has had a great deal of stress at work lately and before she went missing, was anxious to tell her boss that she will not meet the deadline for her current project. She has had two major depressive episodes within the past 4 years that were treated with citalopram. She drinks one to two beers daily and sometimes more on weekends. She does not use illicit drugs. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Physical and neurological examinations show no abnormalities. On mental status exam, she is oriented only to time and place but not to person. Short-term memory is intact; she does not recognize her husband or recall important events of her life.

A 12-year-old healthy male presents for evaluation of rash on the chest and back ongoing for the past 4 days. Mother reports that she first noticed a larger spot on his right flank, then smaller similar lesions began developing all over the chest and back. She denies any history of eczema for the patient or family history. She denies any new topical products. The rash is not painful or itchy. Mother has tried topical over the counter hydrocortisone without any improvement. Physical examination is remarkable for erythematous pink thin papules and plaqueswith overlying fine thin scale on the back and chest. A larger thin scaly plaque is appreciated on the right flank. A KOH preparation is performed and does not reveal any fungal elements

A 5-year-old boy is brought to the physician because of early morning headaches for the past 6 months. During this period, he has had severe nausea and occasional episodes of vomiting. For the past month, he has had difficulty walking and intermittent double vision. He was born at term and has been healthy apart from an episode of sinusitis 8 months ago that resolved spontaneously. He is at the 60th percentile for height and 50th percentile for weight. His temperature is 37.1°C (98.8°F), pulse is 80/min, and blood pressure is 105/64 mm Hg. Examination shows normal muscle strength and 2+ deep tendon reflexes bilaterally. He has a broad-based gait and impaired tandem gait. Fundoscopy shows bilateral swelling of the optic disc. There is esotropia of the left eye.

A 6-year-old girl presents with a 1-year history of a waxing and waning rash on her limbs and face. The rash starts as red scaly bumps that fade over several weeks leaving smooth white spots. Every few months, the patient gets several new red bumps. The rash is not itchy or painful. Her parents have tried topical steroid creams that did not help clear the rash. Examination reveals scattered erythematous scaly papules on both legs and several hypopigmented macules on her legs, arms, and face.

A 52-year-old man comes to the physician for a routine medical check-up. The patient feels well. He has hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and recurrent panic attacks. He had a myocardial infarction 3 years ago. He underwent a left inguinal hernia repair at the age of 25 years. A colonoscopy 2 years ago was normal. He works as a nurse at a local hospital. He is married and has two children. His father died of prostate cancer at the age of 70 years. He had smoked one pack of cigarettes daily for 25 years but quit following his myocardial infarction. He drinks one to two beers on the weekends. He has never used illicit drugs. Current medications include aspirin, atorvastatin, lisinopril, metoprolol, fluoxetine, metformin, and a multivitamin. He appears well-nourished. Temperature is 36.8°C (98.2°F), pulse is 70/min, and blood pressure is 125/75 mm Hg. Lungs are clear to auscultation. Cardiac examination shows a high-frequency, mid-to-late systolic murmur that is best heard at the apex. The abdomen is soft and nontender. The remainder of the physical examination shows no abnormalities.

A 24-year-old woman comes to the physician because of a 2-month history of increased urination. She has also had dry mouth and excessive thirst despite drinking several gallons of water daily. She has a history of obsessive-compulsive disorder treated with citalopram. She drinks 1–2 cans of beer daily. Physical examination shows no abnormalities. Serum studies show a Na+ concentration of 130 mEq/L, a glucose concentration of 185 mg/dL, and an osmolality of 265 mOsmol/kg. Urine osmolality is 230 mOsmol/kg. The patient is asked to stop drinking water for 3 hours. Following water restriction, repeated laboratory studies show a serum osmolality of 280 mOsmol/kg and a urine osmolality of 650 mOsmol/kg.

A 24-year-old Caucasian woman presented with intermittent, inflammatory papulopustules and nodules on the face, neck, chest, and back. The lesions would appear 1 week premenstrually and resolve 1 week postmenstrually with normal menstrual cycles. She has a history of adolescent acne that is only responsive to isotretinoin 6 years ago. Examination revealed scarring and postinflammatory hyperpigmentation diffusely on her face.

A 11-year-old male with past medical history of medulloblastoma is brought to dermatology clinic for evaluation of multiple "moles" on the face, neck, arms and legs. Patient's mother reports developing similar lesions when she was younger and a history of ovarian fibromas.  Examination reveals multiple thin brown pedunculated papules on the cheeks, neck, and upper chest and back. Focal atrophic ovoid papules are appreciated on the palms bilaterally.

A 30-year-old Hispanic woman presents with her 1-year-old son, concerned that he has only small amounts of thin, wispy hair on his head and has none anywhere else on his body. She notes that he does not yet have any teeth, but has a large forehead and ears. He has been irritable and crying for the past day. She reveals a personal history of very high body temperature at times during the summer and says she customarily stays indoors with the air conditioning on, especially in the summer. On physical examination, she has sparse hair on her scalp and eyebrows, as well as eczematous patches on her bilateral lower extremities.

A 12-year-old female presents with hemorrhagic crusts on the lips and erosions of the oral, genital, and conjunctival mucosa for 2 days. According to the parents, there was a pneumonia outbreak at school. The patient also had a high fever and cough a week before the onset of cutaneous lesions. The parents deny any new medication and a history of allergies. The physical exam reveals no other skin findings.

A 34-year-old woman comes to the physician because of recent fatigue and weakness that is exacerbated by cross-country skiing. Four weeks ago, she was diagnosed with pneumonia; sputum cultures on Eaton agar showed organisms that lacked a cell wall. Physical examination shows conjunctival pallor and cyanosis of the fingertips. Both lungs are clear to auscultation.

A 71-year-old man comes to the physician accompanied by his wife because of a 6-month history of worsening episodic upper abdominal pain and an 8-kg (17.6-lb) weight loss. The pain is dull, nonradiating, worse after eating, and occasionally associated with bloating and diarrhea. His symptoms have not improved despite 4 weeks of treatment with omeprazole. He attributes his weight loss to recently eating very small portions and avoiding fatty foods. He has hypertension and hypercholesterolemia. He underwent a coronary artery bypass graft operation for coronary artery disease 8 years ago. Current medications include lisinopril, metoprolol, atorvastatin, and aspirin. He has smoked a pack of cigarettes daily for 20 years and drinks 1–2 beers daily. His pulse is 79/min and blood pressure is 138/89 mm Hg. Examination shows a soft abdomen without tenderness to palpation or guarding.

A 60-year-old man presents to the clinic with a 1-cm long horn-like projection coming from the skin on the superior aspect of the skull just lateral to midline. The structure is yellowish-white in color and feels very firm to the touch. He states that he noticed a small, hard lesion a few months ago and that it has grown progressively larger from the time of initial presentation to now. The patient denies any pain at rest but states that he experiences pain when the lesion is struck accidentally.

A newborn fullterm female is noted to have a patch of hair loss, prominent leg veins, and shortened fingers at birth. Prenatal course was unremarkable. Physical examination reveals an extensive large ulcerated atrophic plaque on the scalp with surrounding peripheral hair, brachydactyly of index fingers, and lacy reticulated violaceous patches on the right thigh and calf.

A 28-year-old healthy white woman with no significant past medical history presents with an enlarging papule on her right lateral neck. She describes a 1- to 2-mm pink papule that grew to approximately 10 mm within the past week. With minimal rubbing or trauma, the papule intermittently bleeds. It is otherwise nontender and nonpruritic. She has no history of skin cancer and is taking oral contraceptives. Physical examination shows a pink, friable papule on a stalk on the right lateral neck. There are no other similar lesions seen on examination.

A 30-year-old male presents for evaluation of a dark discoloration on the posterior thighs present for the past month. He denies any topical products applied to the area. He denies any pain or pruritus at the area. He has not tried any treatments. The rash has been stable in size, is constant, and is not significantly growing in size. He works a desk job and reports sitting on a seat warmer over the past several years. Physical examination reveals reticulated lacy brown patches on the posterior thighs and lower buttocks.

A 45-year-old woman presents with enlarging blood vessels on her tongue that recently have increased in size and number. Numerous 1- to 2-mm discrete red macules and papules are seen on her tongue, oral mucosa, nose, lower lip, and fingertips. She has had frequent nosebleeds since childhood as well as iron-deficiency anemia that has not responded to iron supplementation. Her father, who died at the age of 50, had similar symptoms.

A 56-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department by her husband because of slurred speech and left facial droop for the past 30 minutes. During this period, she has also had numbness on the left side of her face. She has never had such an episode before. She has hypertension, hypercholesterolemia, and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her father died of lung cancer 1 week ago. The patient has smoked one pack of cigarettes daily for 30 years. She drinks one glass of wine daily. Her current medications include metformin, sitagliptin, enalapril, and atorvastatin. She is 168 cm (5 ft 6 in) tall and weighs 86 kg (190 lb); BMI is 30.5 kg/m2. She is oriented to time, place, and person. Her temperature is 37°C (98.7°F), pulse is 97/min, and blood pressure is 140/90 mm Hg. Examination shows drooping of the left side of the face. Her speech is clear. Examination shows full muscle strength. Deep tendon reflexes are 2+ bilaterally. A finger-nose test and her gait are normal. Cardiopulmonary examination shows a right-sided carotid bruit. A complete blood count and serum concentrations of creatinine, glucose, and electrolytes are within the reference ranges. An ECG shows left ventricular hypertrophy. A noncontrast CT scan of the brain shows no abnormalities. On the way back from the CT scan, her presenting symptoms resolve.

A 55-year-old man comes to the physician because of a 6-week history of tingling pain in the sole of his right foot when he raises it above chest level during exercises. He reports that he started exercising regularly 2 months ago and that his right calf cramps when he uses the incline feature on the treadmill, forcing him to take frequent breaks. The pain completely disappears after resting for a few minutes. He has an 8-year history of type 2 diabetes mellitus. He has smoked two packs of cigarettes daily for 34 years. His only medication is metformin. His pulse is 82/min, and blood pressure is 170/92 mm Hg. Straight leg raise test elicits pallor and tingling pain in the right foot. There is no pain in the back. His muscle strength is normal. Femoral pulses are palpable; right pedal pulses are absent.

A 27-year-old man comes to the physician because of worsening abdominal pain over the last several months. He has also had recent feelings of sadness and a lack of motivation at work, where he is employed as a computer programmer. He denies suicidal thoughts. He has a history of multiple kidney stones. He has a family history of thyroid cancer in his father and uncle, who both underwent thyroidectomy before age 30. His temperature is 37°C (98°F), blood pressure is 138/86 mm Hg, and pulse is 87/min. Physical examination shows diffuse tenderness over the abdomen and obesity but is otherwise unremarkable. Serum studies show:
Na+ 141 mEq/L
K+ 3.6 mEq/L
Glucose 144 mg/dL
Ca2+ 12.1 mg/dL
Albumin 4.1 g/dL
PTH 226 pg/mL (normal range 12–88 pg/mL)
Results of a RET gene test return abnormal. The physician refers him to an endocrine surgeon.

A 32-year-old man comes to the physician for a 1-month history of fever, chest pain with deep breathing, and a 4-kg (9 lb) weight loss. His temperature is 38°C (100.4°F). An x-ray of the chest shows a subpleural nodule in the right lower lobe with right hilar lymphadenopathy. Histological examination of a right hilar lymph node biopsy specimen shows several granulomas with acellular cores.

A 54-year-old woman with a history of depression presents to the clinic with a 1-year history of an intermittent rash. She was hospitalized for COVID-19 approximately 1 year ago and soon after developed a rash all over her body. The lesions persist for several days and have a burning sensation. The patient has no associated joint pain or other systemic symptoms. She tried antihistamines for the rash with no symptomatic relief. On examination, erythematous wheals are evident on her arms and legs as well as her back and abdomen.

On day-of-life 2, a 3-day-old boy who was born with no visible skin problems begins to develop erosions and bullae over both the palmar and plantar surfaces. These bullae are localized to areas of friction or trauma (eg, where electrocardiogram leads were placed). The mother’s pregnancy was normal, and the infant had been born without complications. Aside from the development of bullae, the infant has no evidence of any other medical problems. The infant’s parents are healthy and have no medical problems. No one in the infant’s family has had similar dermatologic findings.
